5000|$|The {{structure}} of <b>euchromatin</b> {{is reminiscent of}} an unfolded set of beads along a string, wherein those beads represent nucleosomes. Nucleosomes consist of eight proteins known as histones, with approximately 147 base pairs of DNA wound around them; in <b>euchromatin,</b> this wrapping is loose so that the raw DNA may be accessed. Each core histone possesses a 'tail' structure, which can vary in several ways; {{it is thought that}} these variations act as [...] "master control switches", which determine the overall arrangement of the chromatin. In particular, it is believed that the presence of methylated lysine 4 on the histone tails acts as a general marker for <b>euchromatin.</b>|$|E
